Question:
Print the sum of all elements in the list.

Input:
List<Integer> list = Arrays.asList(4, 5, 6);

Solution:-
Java 8 Streams sum list elements efficiently using mapToInt().sum(). For input [4, 5, 6], it prints 15.

#Step-by-Step Logic
Stream the list via stream(). Convert Integer to primitive int with mapToInt(Integer::intValue). Call sum() on IntStream for total.
​
#Complete Implementation

import java.util.Arrays;
import java.util.List;

public class SumAndPrint {
    public static void sumAndPrint(List<Integer> numbers) {
        int sum = numbers.stream()
                         .mapToInt(Integer::intValue)
                         .sum();
        System.out.println(sum);
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        List<Integer> list = Arrays.asList(4, 5, 6);
        sumAndPrint(list);
    }
}

Prints 15. Avoids boxing overhead; direct primitive summation.
​
#Thought Process
Stream<Integer> can't sum directly; mapToInt unboxes to IntStream.sum(). Alternatives: reduce(0, Integer::sum) or collect(summingInt); mapToInt.sum fastest, primitive-optimized.​

#Edge Cases Analysis
Empty list: Returns 0 (identity for sum).​
Null list: NPE on stream(); null-check.
Null elements: NPE on intValue(); filter first.
Single element: Returns itself.
Overflow: Int wraps (e.g., many INT_MAX); use mapToLong().sum() for safety. Large lists: Parallel ok via parallelStream().
